5000|$|In <b>The</b> Phenomenology <b>of</b> Spirit (1807), G.F.W. Hegel {{described}} the stages in <b>the</b> development <b>of</b> <b>the</b> <b>human</b> Geist (<b>Spirit),</b> by which {{men and women}} progress from ignorance to knowledge, <b>of</b> <b>the</b> self and <b>of</b> <b>the</b> world. Developing Hegel's human-spirit proposition, Karl Marx said that those poles of idealism—"spiritual ignorance" [...] and [...] "self-understanding"—are replaced with material categories, whereby [...] "spiritual ignorance" [...] becomes [...] "alienation" [...] and [...] "self-understanding" [...] becomes man's realisation of his Gattungswesen (species-essence).|$|R
