5000|$|Anatoly Solonitsyn {{at first}} {{did not see}} {{anything}} interesting in this [...] "supporting role" [...] as described by him, which he considered a [...] "rehash" [...] of what was filmed earlier. Initially, the actor did not even understand what was wanted <b>of</b> him despite <b>the</b> fact that he diligently played the [...] "enemy", [...] "a man with a bruised heart", [...] "a man without a future" [...] as was required. But even {{he knew that the}} character was turning out to be similar to a mannequin, as in cheap popular literature. Only a long conversation with the director allowed him to understand her vision <b>of</b> Portnov: <b>the</b> personification <b>of</b> <b>the</b> negative side in <b>the</b> eternal history <b>of</b> <b>the</b> man's struggle with the animal in him in <b>the</b> name <b>of</b> <b>the</b> supreme value - namely, <b>the</b> value <b>of</b> <b>the</b> spirit. The director insisted that the Great Patriotic War was won by the Soviet people because of their high level of awareness, so Portnov's [...] "anti-hero" [...] role was especially important because the character was supposed to emphasize <b>the</b> superiority <b>of</b> <b>the</b> <b>human</b> <b>spirit's</b> power over matter.|$|R
